Problem 1: Multiple Choice¶

For each of the following questions, choose correct options. Each question has AT LEAST one correct option. No explanation is required.

a) Consider a Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) which successfully produces images of apples. Which of the following propositions is false?

  1. The generator aims to learn the distribution of apple images.

  2. The discriminator can be used to classify images as apple vs. non-apple.

  3. After training the GAN, the discriminator loss eventually reaches a constant value.

  4. The generator can produce unseen images of apples.

b) Which of the following costs is the non-saturating generator cost for GANs ($G$ is the generator and $D$ is the discriminator)?

  1. $J^{(G)} = \frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m}\log(1-D(G(z^{(i)})))$
  2. $J^{(G)} = -\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m}\log(D(G(z^{(i)})))$
  3. $J^{(G)} = \frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m}\log(1-G(D(z^{(i)})))$
  4. $J^{(G)} = -\frac{1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{m}\log(G(D(z^{(i)})))$

Solution 1¶

a) 2

b) 2

Problem 2: Short Answers¶

a) One of your friends has trained a cat vs. non-cat classifier. It performs very well and you want to use transfer learning to build your own model. Explain what additional hyperparameters (due to the transfer learning) you will need to tune.

b) You have a dataset D1 with 1 million labelled training examples for classification, and dataset D2 with 100 labelled training examples. Your friend trains a model from scratch on dataset D2. You decide to train on D1, and then apply transfer learning to train on D2. State one problem your friend is likely to find with his approach. How does your approach address this problem?

c) You are training on a GAN to generate cool octopus images. But you are only able to curate a small number of images of actual octopus. You decide that image augmentation might be a good idea to improve GAN training. You try using three common augmentation techniques: adding blur to the image, changing the color of pixels and flipping the left-right axis of the image. Which of these do you think might be a good idea to help the Generator output better octopus images and why?

Solution 2¶

a) The parameters you would need to choose are: 1. How many layers of the original network to keep, 2. How many new layers to introduce, and 3. How many of the layers of the original network would you want to keep frozen while fine tuning.

b) Friend is likely to see overfitting. Model is not going to generalise well to unseen data. By using transfer learning and freezing the weights in the earlier layers, you reduce the number of learnable parameters, while using the weights which have been pretrained on a much larger dataset.

c) We should only use left-right flip augmentation, as the other ones will create artifacts in the generated images like having unreal colors or generating blurred images.

Problem 4: GAN¶

Recall that a GAN could, in principle, be trained using the following minimax formulation, where G is the generator function, D is the probability the discriminator assigns to the sample being data, and $J_D$ and $J_G$ are the cost functions for the discriminator and generator, respectively.


$$ \begin{align*} \mathcal J_{D} &= E_{x \sim p_{\text{data}}(x)}\left[-\log D(x)\right] + E_{z \sim p_{z}(z)}\left[-\log (1-D(G(z)))\right] \\\\ \mathcal J_{G} &= \text{const} + E_{z \sim p_{z}(z)}\left[\log (1-D(G(z)))\right] \end{align*}$$


However, in practice, the generator is usually trained with a different loss function.

a) What cost function do we typically use for the generator? (Cost function after the modification)

b) What is the reason to use the cost function you wrote in part a) rather than the one given above?

Solution 4¶

a) $ -\log (D(G(z)))$

b) In the minimax formulation, the generator’s loss saturates when the generator is doing very badly (i.e. when the discriminator can easily recognize its samples as fake). The alternative objective puts a large emphasis on small differences in $D(G(z))$ when $D(G(z))$ is close to 0, so that the generator still has a strong gradient signal in this case.

Problem 5: Markov Chain¶

Let $ W =$ Workday and $ D = $ Day Off. We observe the following sequence of Workdays and Days Off:




Note: Sunday the $23^{rd}$ will be considered the first day (i.e., $\text{Day } 1$).

a) What is the probability that the first day is a workday (i.e., $P(\text{Day } 1 = \text{Workday})$)

b) What is the probability that the first day is a day off (i.e., $P(\text{Day }1 = \text{Day Off})$)

c) What is the probability that today will be a workday given that yesterday was a workday (i.e., $P(\text{Day } t = \text{Workday} \mid \text{Day } t-1 = \text{Workday})$)

d) What is the probability that today will be a day off given that yesterday was a workday (i.e., $P(\text{Day } t = \text{Day off} \mid \text{Day } t-1 = \text{Workday})$)

e) What is the probability that today will be a workday given that yesterday was a day off (i.e., $P(\text{Day } t = \text{Workday} \mid \text{Day } t-1 = \text{Day Off})$)

f) What is the probability that today will be a day off given that yesterday was a day off (i.e., $P(\text{Day } t = \text{Day Off} \mid \text{Day } t-1 = \text{Day Off})$)

g) Bulid the state trasition probability matrix.

Solution 5¶

a) $P(\text{Day } 1 = \text{Workday}) = 1$

b) $P(\text{Day }1 = \text{Day Off}) = 0$

c)

  • Count of Workday followed by a Workday (#WW) = 27
  • Count of Workday followed by a Day Off (#WD) = 3


$$P(\text{Day } t = \text{Workday} \mid \text{Day } t-1 = \text{Workday}) = \frac{\text{#WW}}{\text{#WW} + \text{#WD}} = \frac{27}{27 + 3} = \frac{27}{30} =0.9 $$


d)

  • Count of Workday followed by a Workday (#WW) = 27
  • Count of Workday followed by a Day Off (#WD) = 3


$$P(\text{Day } t = \text{Day Off} \mid \text{Day } t-1 = \text{Workday}) = \frac{\text{#WD}}{\text{#WW} + \text{#WD}} = \frac{3}{27 + 3} = \frac{3}{30} =0.1 $$


e)

  • Count of Day Off followed by a Workday (#WW) = 3
  • Count of Day Off followed by a Day Off (#WD) = 1


$$P(\text{Day } t = \text{Workday} \mid \text{Day } t-1 = \text{Day Off}) = \frac{\text{#DW}}{\text{#DW} + \text{#DD}} = \frac{3}{3 + 1} = \frac{3}{4} =0.75 $$


f)

  • Count of Day Off followed by a Workday (#WW) = 3
  • Count of Day Off followed by a Day Off (#WD) = 1


$$P(\text{Day } t = \text{Day Off} \mid \text{Day } t-1 = \text{Day Off}) = \frac{\text{#DD}}{\text{#DW} + \text{#DD}} = \frac{1}{3 + 1} = \frac{1}{4} =0.25 $$

g)


$$ \left(\begin{array}{cc} 0.9 & 0.1\\ 0.75 & 0.25 \end{array}\right) $$

Problem 7: Statistical Anomaly Detection¶

Let $P = (0,0),Q = (1,0),R = (0,3) ∈ R^2$, and $f : R^2 → R^2$ be an isometry such that $ f(P) = (0,2), f(Q) = (−1,2) $and $f(R) = (0,5)$. Consider the points $S =(−3,0)$.

Hint 1: Isometry is a distance-preserving transformation between metric spaces

Hint 2: For isometry, following equations are satisfied:


$$ \begin{align*} d(P,S) &= d(f(P),f(S))\\ d(Q,S) &= d(f(Q),f(S))\\ d(R,S) &= d(f(R),f(S)) \end{align*}$$



a) Find the Euclidean distances $d(P,S),d(Q,S),d(R,S)$

b) Find the image $f(S)$ of the point $S ∈ R^2$.

c) Pick a point among $P, Q, R$ with the highest probability of being an anomaly based on its distance from $S$ in a sense of Euclidean distances.

Solution 7¶

a) The Euclidean distance is $ d((x_1 , y_1) , (x_2 , y_2)) = \sqrt{(x_1 - x_2)^2 + (y_1 - y_2)^2}$. Hence $d(P, S) = 3$ , $d(Q,S) = 4$, $d(R, S) = 3\sqrt 2 $

b) $f(S) = (3,2)$

c) R

Problem 8: Self-supervised Learning¶

a) Prof. Lee has explained about various pretext tasks you can use for the self-supervised learning. Choose one pretext task and explain the mechanism of that pretext task for self-supervised learning in detail. (Exclude the Rotation Network)

b) Draw the model (network) used in the pretext task chosen at (1) and explain in detail (Specify the function of each part of the model)

  • You may use figures in articles

c) Explain downstream tasks that the pretext task specified at (1) can be applied

Solution 8¶

a) Context Prediction is a pretext task that creates nine 3x3-shaped patches from an input image and then finds out the relative position of an arbitrary patch based on the patch located in the middle. In Context Prediction, the input is a center patch and one non-center patch, and the output is a value representing the relative position of the non-center patch from 1 to 8. Context Prediction is a type of Self-supervised Learning because a patch can be created from an input image and a label can be automatically generated even if a person does not directly create a label by selecting a random patch.

b) Since the input of Context Prediction is two patches, there are two branches in the network that receive each of two patches. Two branches share the same weights and there is a final layer that aggregates the results of two branches and use them to make predictions.



c) The model trained through the pretext task described above can obtain features of images very well. After fixing the weights of the model, downstream tasks like classification can be performed based on the obtain features.

Problem 9: PINN¶

Cost function of PINN can be written as below. Describe what each terms in the cost function means when the given ODE system is $ {u^\prime} = f(u,t)$ with $t \in [0, 1]$ and a known initial condition $u(0) = u_0$. $ {\text{NN}(t)}$ is the solution by a neural network.



$${L(\omega)} = \sum_{i} \left(\frac{d \text{NN}(t_i)}{dt}-f(\text{NN}(t_i),t_i)\right)^2 + (\text{NN}(0)-u_0)^2 $$

Solution 9¶

  • $\sum_{i} \left(\frac{d \text{NN}(t_i)}{dt}-f(\text{NN}(t_i),t_i)\right)^2$ : ODE Loss
  • $(\text{NN}(0)-u_0)^2$ : Initial Condition Loss

Problem 11: GCN¶

a) Define three situations (problems) where you can apply Graph Convolution Network

b) For the three situation mentioned above, write which task among the three task type of Graph Neural Network each situation belongs to and explain why.

c) Describe two commonalities and two differences that GCNs have with CNNs

Solution 11¶

a)

  • Traffic forecasting
  • Social influence analysis in SNS
  • Materials Property Analysis

b)

  • After setting each place as a node, it can be used to search for the shortest route from a specific node to another node, and the road connecting each place can be set as an edge, so GCN is used. (Edge prediction)
  • Each person is set as a node, and the influence between people can be analyzed by using the characteristics of each person's SNS account as a property. GCN is suitable for connecting people and utilizing additional information. (Node classification/Edge prediction)
  • Structural information can be acquired by displaying materials with molecular structures through graphs. By setting atoms as nodes and bonds as edges and extracting structural characteristics of molecules, it is possible to analyze the chemical properties of new materials with GCN. (Graph classification)

c)

Commonality

  • They use nodes that are centered at a specific location (learns the features by inspecting neighboring nodes)
  • Calculations are performed using the kernel


Difference

  • CNN uses data with a fixed size
  • In the data used by GCN, nodes are connected in several ways
  • There are no rules for where nodes are located in the data used by GCN.

Problem 12: GCN¶

In the GCN layer, feature representation for layer $k+1$ can be written as $ H^{(k+1)} = \sigma (AH^{(k)} W^{(k)}) $.

a) By adding message passing with self-loops and neighborhood normalization on the equation, derive the final equation of feature representation for layer $k+1$

b) Describe briefly about the roles of message passing with self-loops and neighborhood normalization

Solution 12¶

a) $$ \begin{align*} H^{(k+1)} &= \sigma \left(A H^{(k)} \, W^{(k)} \right) \\\\ &\Downarrow \\\\ H^{(k+1)} &= \sigma \left( \left(A+I \right)H^{(k)} \, W^{(k)}\right) \\\\ &\Downarrow \\\\ H^{(k+1)} &= \sigma \left( \left(\tilde D^{-1/2}(A+I)\tilde D^{-1/2} \right)H^{(k)} \, W^{(k)}\right)\\\\\\ \therefore H^{(k+1)} &= \sigma \left( \tilde A H^{(k)} \, W^{(k)}\right) \end{align*} $$

b)

  • Message passing with self-loops: It is the process of integrating features of itself and surrounding nodes.
  • Neighborhood normalization: Normalize the neighborhood aggregation operation based upon the degrees of the nodes involved
